  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 21.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "In those days",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Or, \"at that time\" - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " at the time when the second gathering of the virgins took place (see ver. 19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "). Two of the king's chamberlains",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Rather, \"eunuchs.\" Bigthan, or Bigthana (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Esther 6:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), is probably the same name as the Bigtha of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Esther 1:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and possibly the same personage. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Teresh",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is not mentioned elsewhere. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Of those which kept the door",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Two of the eunuchs who guarded the entrance to the king's sleeping apartment. This was a position of the highest possible trust, and gave conspirators a terrible advantage. Xerxes actually lost his life through a conspiracy formed by Artabanus, the captain of his guard, with Aspamitras, a eunuch and chamberlain (Ctes., 'Exc. Pers.,' § 29). Esther 2:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The definition of time in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Esther 2:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is again take up by the words: in those days; then the explanatory clause, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Esther 2:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is repeated; and after this we are informed what it was that had then occurred. In those days Bigthan and Teresh, two of the king's courtiers, who were the threshold-keepers (palace-watchers, lxx ἀρχισωματοφύλακες), were wroth, and sought to lay hands on King Ahashverosh, i.e., to slay him. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Esther 2:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This thing was known to Mordochai, and by him communicated to Esther, who told it, in Mordochai's name, to the king. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Esther 2:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The matter was investigated (sc. by the king), and found out, sc. as Mordochai had testified. The two criminals were hanged on a tree, i.e., impaled on a stake, a sort of crucifixion, - see rem. on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Esther 6:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", - and the circumstance entered in the book of the chronicles, i.e., the chronicles of the kingdom. המּלך לפני, before the king, i.e., in his presence, immediately after sentence had been passed by a court over which the monarch presided. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]